WEBVTT

00:01.807 --> 00:04.008
Look, I know you guys don't want
to do this,

00:04.010 --> 00:05.142
but we have no choice.

00:05.144 --> 00:06.511
So, you can either
bitch and whine

00:06.513 --> 00:08.012
or we can
just get it over with.

00:08.013 --> 00:08.896
I got "whine."

00:08.898 --> 00:10.565
I got the "b word."

00:10.567 --> 00:12.717
Yeah, well,
it's in our contract

00:12.719 --> 00:14.402
to serve on a
university committee.

00:14.404 --> 00:15.403
And frankly,

00:15.405 --> 00:16.654
this is one I believe in.

00:16.656 --> 00:17.989
Okay, here we go.

00:17.991 --> 00:20.891
Encouraging more women to
pursue a career in the sciences.

00:20.893 --> 00:22.326
Come on,
if I was any good

00:22.328 --> 00:23.727
at convincing women to do stuff,

00:23.729 --> 00:26.497
I wouldn't have spent so much of
my 20s in the shower.

00:28.116 --> 00:29.183
If you ask me,

00:29.185 --> 00:31.002
this whole thing is a waste of
our time.

00:31.004 --> 00:32.253
Helping women?

00:32.255 --> 00:34.905
Yeah, helping anyone.

00:34.907 --> 00:37.291
People should take care
of themselves.

00:37.293 --> 00:38.843
Oh, like yesterday,

00:38.845 --> 00:41.045
when you made me drive you
to the dry cleaners,

00:41.047 --> 00:42.913
the pharmacy
and the post office?

00:42.915 --> 00:45.683
I'm not saying people
can't use tools.

00:47.286 --> 00:50.354
Even an otter picks up a rock
when he wants a clam.

00:51.773 --> 00:52.940
You don't think it's worthwhile

00:52.942 --> 00:55.026
to try to get more women
working in science.

00:55.028 --> 00:57.194
I think
that's incredibly sexist of you.

00:57.196 --> 00:59.530
I believe in a
gender-blind society

00:59.532 --> 01:02.533
like in <i>Star Trek,</i>
where women and men

01:02.535 --> 01:06.120
of all races and creeds
work side by side as equals.

01:06.122 --> 01:08.623
You mean
where they were advanced enough

01:08.625 --> 01:10.675
to invent
an interstellar warp drive,

01:10.677 --> 01:14.078
but a black lady still answered
the space phone?

01:15.080 --> 01:16.714
Oh, I did spend a lot of my

01:16.716 --> 01:18.666
shower time
with Lieutenant Uhura.

01:20.052 --> 01:23.454
Howard's
disturbing recollections aside,

01:23.456 --> 01:25.840
I don't appreciate
being forced to do

01:25.842 --> 01:26.974
banal committee work.

01:26.976 --> 01:28.893
Yes, I know,
you're too smart for this.

01:28.895 --> 01:29.877
Exactly.

01:29.879 --> 01:31.345
It's like
asking the Human Torch

01:31.347 --> 01:34.065
to heat up your frozen burrito.

01:34.067 --> 01:35.149
Got it.

01:35.151 --> 01:37.151
All right,
I'm thinking one way

01:37.153 --> 01:39.070
to counter bias
in the peer-review process,

01:39.072 --> 01:41.522
is for papers to be submitted
under gender-neutral names.

01:41.524 --> 01:42.907
Like S. Smith

01:42.909 --> 01:44.158
instead of Samantha Smith.

01:44.160 --> 01:46.944
I suppose there is a history of
professional women

01:46.946 --> 01:49.614
using their initials,
so as not to be pre-judged.

01:49.616 --> 01:51.866
<i>Harry Potter's</i> J.K. Rowling,

01:51.868 --> 01:54.035
uh, <i>Star Trek's</i> D.C. Fontana.

01:54.037 --> 01:57.088
Van Nuys pole-dancer
D.D. Melons.

01:59.424 --> 02:01.876
All right, I think we've
really helped women today.

02:01.878 --> 02:03.427
Let's fire
up the old Xbox.

02:03.429 --> 02:05.713
Guys, please don't make this
a school project

02:05.715 --> 02:07.548
where I'm the smart kid doing
all the work

02:07.550 --> 02:09.183
while the slackers
sit back and watch.

02:09.185 --> 02:10.434
No, we're not.

02:10.436 --> 02:11.786
This time you're the smart
kid doing all the work

02:11.788 --> 02:14.639
while the even smarter kids
sit back and watch.

02:15.557 --> 02:17.608
So, you think I'm
one of the smarter kids?

02:17.610 --> 02:20.111
No, you're a tool I was
using to make my point.

