Excuse me,
I'm meeting a girl here.

09:39.682 --> 09:40.981
It's kind of our first date.

09:40.983 --> 09:43.534
In a library?

09:43.536 --> 09:46.520
She and I
are both a little awkward

09:46.522 --> 09:49.740
in social situations,
so this seemed like a good idea.

09:49.742 --> 09:54.795
People say
I'm a little awkward, too.

09:54.797 --> 09:56.680
May I join you?

09:56.682 --> 09:59.750
No, you can't join us.

09:59.752 --> 10:01.552
Just go-go climb back up

10:01.554 --> 10:04.004
whatever beanstalk you came
down from.

10:09.394 --> 10:11.228
You can do better.

10:15.967 --> 10:18.018
Oh, we're eating here?

10:24.159 --> 10:26.076
We're having
a texting date?

10:30.498 --> 10:31.916
<i>I love that.</i>

10:35.069 --> 10:38.238
<i>As you're reading,</i>
<i>it will help to remember</i>

10:38.240 --> 10:42.293
<i>I have an adorable accent.</i>

10:44.629 --> 10:49.600
Okay,
who's ready for some science?

10:53.087 --> 10:55.255
Me, too.

10:55.257 --> 10:57.391
Okay, I am
Dr. Leonard Hofstadter.

10:57.393 --> 10:59.143
I am here with my friends
Dr. Cooper

10:59.145 --> 11:02.529
and real-life astronaut
Howard Wolowitz,

11:02.531 --> 11:04.148
and we are going
to show you girls

11:04.150 --> 11:07.901
how cool a job
in science can be.

11:07.903 --> 11:09.119
How cool, you ask?

11:09.121 --> 11:12.156
Well, how about
negative 273 degrees,

11:12.158 --> 11:13.240
'cause that's the temperature

11:13.242 --> 11:16.927
at which entropy reaches
its minimum value.

11:18.947 --> 11:21.832
Did I just learn something new
and have fun doing it?

11:21.834 --> 11:24.134
What?

11:26.471 --> 11:29.073
All right!

11:29.075 --> 11:31.058
So now let's bring out

11:31.060 --> 11:32.959
theoretical physicist

11:32.961 --> 11:36.347
Dr. Sheldon Cooper.

11:40.769 --> 11:42.936
Hello, female children.

11:43.805 --> 11:46.874
Allow me to inspire you

11:46.876 --> 11:50.544
with a story
about a great female scientist.

11:50.546 --> 11:55.499
Polish-born, French-educated
Madame Curie.

11:55.501 --> 11:57.368
Codiscoverer of
radioactivity,

11:57.370 --> 11:59.336
she was a hero

11:59.338 --> 12:03.173
of science...
until her hair fell out;

12:03.175 --> 12:06.593
her vomit and stool became
filled with blood...

12:06.595 --> 12:08.228
and she was poisoned

12:08.230 --> 12:11.098
to death by her own discovery.

12:12.467 --> 12:14.018
With a little hard work,

12:14.020 --> 12:17.971
I see no reason why
that can't happen to any of you.

12:21.192 --> 12:22.643
Are we done?

12:22.645 --> 12:24.795
Can we go?

12:32.342 --> 12:34.542
The thing to remember is

12:34.544 --> 12:36.761
you can go to outer space, too.

12:36.763 --> 12:38.630
I mean, look at me.

12:38.632 --> 12:40.998
I went to this very school.

12:41.000 --> 12:43.718
Those desks you're sitting in,

12:43.720 --> 12:46.220
I was once superglued
to one of them.

12:49.007 --> 12:50.108
Did you go to the moon?

12:50.110 --> 12:52.193
No, but I did go

12:52.195 --> 12:55.313
to the
International Space Station.

12:55.315 --> 12:56.180
Did you fly the rocket?

12:56.182 --> 12:57.765
No,

12:57.767 --> 13:00.518
but I was in the rocket.

13:00.520 --> 13:02.186
I didn't actually...

13:02.188 --> 13:04.289
So you just flew around?
That's kind of like my uncle.

13:04.291 --> 13:05.690
He's a flight attendant.

13:10.129 --> 13:11.296
No...

13:11.298 --> 13:12.714
I'm an American hero.

13:12.716 --> 13:14.699
Your uncle
brings people nuts, okay?

13:14.701 --> 13:18.002
Boy, we are learning
a lot here, huh?

13:18.004 --> 13:20.221
Thank you, astronaut Howard.

13:21.791 --> 13:24.225
Um, I am what's called
an experimental physicist,

13:24.227 --> 13:28.146
which is super-fun,
because I get to test theories

13:28.148 --> 13:29.480
and work with lasers.

13:29.482 --> 13:30.782
Yes?

13:30.784 --> 13:32.900
How did you decide
to become a scientist?

13:32.902 --> 13:34.352
Uh, excellent question.

13:34.354 --> 13:38.222
Um, I suppose I've always been
into science, you know...

13:38.224 --> 13:40.057
My mother and father
are scientists,

13:40.059 --> 13:42.059
so I was kind of led
in that direction.

13:42.061 --> 13:44.862
Eh, pushed might be
a better way to describe it.

13:44.864 --> 13:46.614
To be honest
with you guys,

13:46.616 --> 13:47.915
when I was your age,

13:47.917 --> 13:49.784
I wanted to be a rap star.

13:51.003 --> 13:52.203
Like Snoop Dogg,

13:52.205 --> 13:54.405
but with a healthy respect
for the police.

13:56.508 --> 13:58.259
Yeah, no, sure, you laugh.

13:58.261 --> 14:00.795
Just like my mother did.

14:01.597 --> 14:04.081
After I confided,
I was derided

14:04.083 --> 14:05.667
and chided,
my moms and I collided.

14:05.669 --> 14:07.918
She said my dreams
were misguided.

14:13.225 --> 14:16.427
That's just a little freestyle.

14:19.064 --> 14:21.866
<i>My dad's a gynecologist</i>
<i>in India,</i>

14:21.868 --> 14:24.435
<i>so if you're over there</i>
<i>and need a check up,</i>

14:24.437 --> 14:27.938
<i>as he likes to say,</i>
<i>he's "at your cervix."</i>

14:32.711 --> 14:34.829
<i>That's terrible.</i>

14:34.831 --> 14:37.598
<i>Your dad should be sent</i>
<i>to the pun-itentiary.</i>

14:42.137 --> 14:44.172
<i>That's a fitting</i>

14:44.174 --> 14:45.673
<i>pun-ishment.</i>

14:50.562 --> 14:52.930
<i>I still don't know</i>
<i>what you do for a living.</i>

14:54.633 --> 14:57.235
<i>Web design.</i>

14:59.805 --> 15:02.090
<i>Anything I might have seen?</i>

15:03.525 --> 15:05.610
<i>I don't know.</i>

15:05.612 --> 15:07.712
<i>You ever look</i>
<i>at porn Web sites?</i>

15:18.474 --> 15:20.508
<i>No, never.</i>

15:20.510 --> 15:22.760
<i>What is porn?</i>

15:25.631 --> 15:27.749
<i>Sorry. Autocorrect.</i>

15:27.751 --> 15:29.767
<i>That was supposed to say</i>

15:29.769 --> 15:32.002
<i>"prom Web sites."</i>

15:35.691 --> 15:39.076
<i>Ooh, fun. I love prom.</i>

15:39.078 --> 15:40.545
<i>The romance, the gowns,</i>

15:40.547 --> 15:43.114
<i>it's like a fairy tale come</i>
<i>to life.</i>

15:51.290 --> 15:52.723
<i>Sorry. Autocorrect.</i>

15:52.725 --> 15:53.958
<i>That was supposed to say,</i>

15:53.960 --> 15:56.327
<i>"I like sports."</i>

15:59.214 --> 16:02.650
I never wanted to play
the cello.

16:03.886 --> 16:06.254
How do you meet girls
playing the cello?

16:06.256 --> 16:08.089
"Hey, you want
to come over to my house

16:08.091 --> 16:09.574
"and listen to me play
an instrument

16:09.576 --> 16:11.809
that sounds like
a suicidal bumblebee?"

16:12.978 --> 16:14.846
Quick,
pull the fire alarm.

16:14.848 --> 16:17.064
Let's get out of here.

16:17.066 --> 16:18.649
Uh, hello again.

16:18.651 --> 16:22.520
Um, yeah, I don't know
if women in general

16:22.522 --> 16:26.107
have been actively discouraged
from pursuing the sciences,

16:26.109 --> 16:31.061
but it's clear you young women
here, today, have been.

16:35.167 --> 16:38.419
While I was listening to
my colleagues waste your time,

16:38.421 --> 16:41.906
it occurred to me that it
might be much more meaningful

16:41.908 --> 16:44.208
to hear about women in science

16:44.210 --> 16:46.761
from actual women in science,

16:46.763 --> 16:49.764
and, uh, I happen to know
two brilliant examples

16:49.766 --> 16:53.050
who have agreed to speak
to you on the phone right now.

16:53.052 --> 16:56.554
Uh, Dr. Rostenkowski,
Dr. Fowler, are you there?

16:56.556 --> 16:58.689
We're here.

16:58.691 --> 17:01.309
Thank you for taking time
out of your very busy schedule

17:01.311 --> 17:04.228
to enlighten these young women.

17:04.230 --> 17:06.931
It's our pleasure.

17:10.536 --> 17:12.904
I'm Dr. Fowler, and
I'm a neuroscientist.

17:12.906 --> 17:15.105
And I'm
Dr. Rostenkowski Wolowitz,

17:15.107 --> 17:16.707
and I'm a microbiologist.

17:16.709 --> 17:19.292
The world of science
needs more women,

17:19.295 --> 17:22.579
but from a young age, we
girls are encouraged to care

17:22.582 --> 17:24.214
more about the way we look

17:24.217 --> 17:27.551
than about the
power of our minds.

17:29.154 --> 17:30.788
That's true.

17:30.790 --> 17:32.673
Every one of you has
the capacity

17:32.675 --> 17:34.508
to be anything you want to be.

17:34.510 --> 17:37.962
Unless you want
to be Cinderella.

17:37.964 --> 17:39.513
Come at me.

17:39.515 --> 17:41.015
See what happens.

17:44.086 --> 17:46.470
<i>This was really fun.</i>

17:48.306 --> 17:52.109
My battery's dying,
so I'm just gonna talk.

17:52.111 --> 17:54.362
Thanks for today.

17:54.364 --> 17:56.981
I've been trying to do
more things that scare me,

17:56.983 --> 17:59.984
and coming here
was definitely one of them.

18:00.786 --> 18:02.420
But it was also really nice.

18:02.422 --> 18:05.423
So thanks, and, um,

18:05.425 --> 18:06.958
I'm gonna go.

18:11.013 --> 18:14.265
Maybe I could do
one more scary thing

18:14.267 --> 18:17.668
before I go
and give you a kiss good-bye?

18:17.670 --> 18:19.186
You know,

18:19.188 --> 18:21.272
if that's okay.

18:24.476 --> 18:27.278
Okay.

18:28.814 --> 18:30.998
Panic attack!
Maybe next time.

18:35.186 --> 18:37.354
I'm counting that as foreplay.

18:46.631 --> 18:47.871
Bernie,

18:47.872 --> 18:50.022
I'm home.

18:50.024 --> 18:51.874
You have fun today?

18:51.876 --> 18:55.128
Yes, and I have a
surprise for you.

18:55.130 --> 18:58.764
Please be Cinderella.
Please be Cinderella.

18:58.766 --> 19:02.251
Well, hello, Prince Charming.

19:05.839 --> 19:08.374
Milady.

19:20.104 --> 19:23.189
Hey, how was your... what?

19:23.191 --> 19:24.774
I can explain.

19:24.776 --> 19:26.359
I played hooky with the girls,

19:26.361 --> 19:28.578
then we all went to Disneyland
and got...

19:28.580 --> 19:29.829
What are you doing?

19:29.831 --> 19:32.949
Disneyland. Go on,
I'm listening.

19:35.285 --> 19:41.007
Sheldon, all Snow White needs
is one little kiss to wake up.

19:41.009 --> 19:43.686
Heard you the first time.

